      <h2>Hot Water Cylinders and Formby Property Needs</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Formby's larger properties have specific hot water demands that older vented systems cannot meet. Here is what drives most L37 cylinder work.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Formby Multi-Bathroom Properties and Unvented Cylinders</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0 0 0.5rem;line-height:1.65;">Larger 4 and 5 bedroom Formby properties with two or three bathrooms frequently experience hot water pressure problems when multiple outlets are used simultaneously. The root cause is almost always a vented gravity-fed cylinder system, which delivers pressure based on the height difference between the loft tank and the outlet   and that pressure is shared across every outlet drawing hot water at the same time.</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">An unvented cylinder is fed directly from the mains and delivers hot water at mains pressure to every outlet simultaneously. Running a shower, a bath and the hot kitchen tap at the same time is not a problem with a properly sized unvented system. For a typical 4 bedroom Formby property, a 200 to 250 litre unvented cylinder is usually the right specification. We size the cylinder correctly at the free survey based on the property's bathroom count and hot water demand.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Formby Loft Conversions and Cold Water Tank Removal</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Formby is an active area for loft conversions, and many of these projects require the cold water storage tank to be removed from the loft space to maximise usable headroom and floor area. If the home has a vented hot water system fed from this loft tank, removing the tank requires converting the system to an unvented cylinder. This is a G3 regulated installation   it cannot be carried out by a general plumber without the specific qualification. Our engineers are G3 qualified. We co-ordinate with your loft conversion contractor to ensure the cylinder work is timed correctly within the project, and we issue the G3 commissioning certificate and notify Building Control on completion. Unvented cylinder supply and fit from £900.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">En Suite Additions in Formby Properties</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">When adding an en suite to a Formby master bedroom, the hot water system needs to be capable of supplying the new bathroom at adequate pressure alongside all existing bathrooms. If the existing system is vented, adding a third bathroom often exposes the pressure limitations of the gravity-fed system. We assess the hot water system capacity at the free survey for every Formby bathroom installation and advise whether the existing cylinder is adequate or whether an unvented upgrade is the right move. En suite installation and unvented cylinder upgrade can be combined in a single fixed-price project for maximum convenience.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
